WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.920
 So it's important from time to time to talk about ways that you as a web application developer

00:00:05.920 --> 00:00:09.840
 have a responsibility to create secure web applications.

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:13.280
 And so I want to call your attention to places where you write code

00:00:13.280 --> 00:00:17.880
 that seems like on the surface that it's what could go wrong,

00:00:17.880 --> 00:00:22.160
 and then you realize, oh, wait a sec, that could go wrong.

00:00:22.160 --> 00:00:27.400
 So it turns out that you take data from the user in the request object,

00:00:27.400 --> 00:00:35.320
 whether it's from a form or from the URL, and like s=42 seems innocuous enough.

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:40.560
 And then what I did is I just concatenated that into HTML, and I sent that back.

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:46.800
 And so the problem is, is what if somebody with ill intent tries to produce data that

00:00:46.800 --> 00:00:48.880
 actually does something?

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:52.760
 And the problem is, is if I take data straight from the user

00:00:52.760 --> 00:00:59.480
 and put it back in the HTML response, well, HTML and JavaScript are programming language.

00:00:59.480 --> 00:01:01.280
 Your browser is being programmed.

00:01:01.280 --> 00:01:07.640
 And that means that a user typing data into your system can program the browser.

00:01:07.640 --> 00:01:15.120
 And what's even worse is that having them program their own browser, not such a big deal.

00:01:15.120 --> 00:01:22.000
 But in a way, what they do is they put some data in your system that turns into code,

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.960
 and then they kidnap someone else's browser when they take a look at data that came in.

00:01:26.960 --> 00:01:32.920
 This is called cross-site scripting, where in a sense, what it's doing is it's trying

00:01:32.920 --> 00:01:39.080
 to run code so that it can read stuff from your site and then hand it to a rogue site.

00:01:39.080 --> 00:01:42.040
 And so we have to protect against this.

00:01:42.040 --> 00:01:43.960
 And it's a very simple thing.

00:01:43.960 --> 00:01:50.840
 So if we take a look at the code that was bad, basically, we have this parameter guess.

00:01:50.840 --> 00:01:53.600
 And the last time I showed you, that was 42.

00:01:53.600 --> 00:01:58.080
 And we just took this request, get guess, which is this stuff.

00:01:58.080 --> 00:02:02.720
 And we simply concatenated it into some HTML.

00:02:02.720 --> 00:02:11.440
 Well, if I carefully construct my guess with %c3, blah, blah, blah, all that stuff, well,

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:21.120
 that turns into-- this is a URL encoding of less than, be bold, greater than, bold, slash.

00:02:21.120 --> 00:02:23.220
 So that turns into HTML.

00:02:23.220 --> 00:02:27.640
 So I passed into this application some HTML.

00:02:27.640 --> 00:02:32.900
 And I, as the developer, took that and I concatenated it together.

00:02:32.900 --> 00:02:36.900
 So the response source has HTML.

00:02:36.900 --> 00:02:42.460
 It's HTML that mostly comes from the application, but this little bit of HTML came from the

00:02:42.460 --> 00:02:43.560
 person who put it in.

00:02:43.560 --> 00:02:50.840
 And like I said, it's not such a critical problem if I, in my browser, put stuff to

00:02:50.840 --> 00:02:52.840
 take over your browser.

00:02:52.840 --> 00:02:56.900
 But it is if you can move that into someone else's browser.

00:02:56.900 --> 00:03:05.320
 So what happens is that the browser sees this bold text in HTML, and instead of showing

00:03:05.320 --> 00:03:08.840
 us the less than and the greater than, it actually shows it to us as bold.

00:03:08.840 --> 00:03:15.000
 Now, this seems innocuous enough until you do something much more clever.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:23.440
 And that is I am going to carefully construct some code, JavaScript.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:29.800
 And so what happens is, is this here is encoding of that line right there, the script alert

00:03:29.800 --> 00:03:32.400
 owned slash script.

00:03:32.400 --> 00:03:37.560
 And so what happens is, is that came in and it was concatenated straight out.

00:03:37.560 --> 00:03:43.900
 And if you run this page, you won't see the data, but that actually JavaScript will run

00:03:43.900 --> 00:03:48.360
 and it's going to show up in an alert box that says owned and okay.

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:52.960
 Now, you can go ahead and look at the Wikipedia entries on cross-site scripting.

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:57.360
 Generally, the idea is, is once you're in JavaScript, you don't just say alert that

00:03:57.360 --> 00:04:01.420
 I've owned your browser, what you do is you do something like grab a cookie and send it

00:04:01.420 --> 00:04:09.680
 to a third party or you call say a web service on the system with a cookie and do bad things.

00:04:09.680 --> 00:04:14.040
 Like you can convince a teacher to log in and change someone else's grade or delete

00:04:14.040 --> 00:04:16.360
 all the grades in a class.

00:04:16.360 --> 00:04:22.260
 Once you're into a person's browser in JavaScript, you can do a lot.

00:04:22.260 --> 00:04:27.280
 So that's really quite scary and there's all kinds of scenarios where you're taking data

00:04:27.280 --> 00:04:32.160
 from the user and you got to be careful because yes, I said the guess is supposed to be a

00:04:32.160 --> 00:04:38.560
 number, but if it's not a number, if I concatenate it without escaping it, it's a problem.

00:04:38.560 --> 00:04:41.680
 So here is a safer version of that.

00:04:41.680 --> 00:04:48.420
 So I've got another view function called game and it takes that same request and it still

00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:53.080
 pulls that get data off, which is this bit right here.

00:04:53.080 --> 00:05:01.680
 But then it calls a function and that's Django utils HTML escape.

00:05:01.680 --> 00:05:08.760
 So what that does is that concatenates that into the HTML, but escape processes any dangerous

00:05:08.760 --> 00:05:12.260
 characters and turns them into what are called HTML entities.

00:05:12.260 --> 00:05:19.520
 So less than becomes ampersand LT, greater than becomes ampersand GT.

00:05:19.520 --> 00:05:24.120
 These four things with ampersands are a safer version of it and so that means that even

00:05:24.120 --> 00:05:28.680
 though I tried, I put in the data for bold, it comes out with the less than and greater

00:05:28.680 --> 00:05:32.880
 than showing and it's not actually interpreted.

00:05:32.880 --> 00:05:40.220
 So this whole notion of escaping or HTML entities, converting data, running the data from a user

00:05:40.220 --> 00:05:45.720
 through an HTML entities automatic filter ensures that the user cannot provide you data

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:51.260
 that turns into code in there or someone else's browser eventually.

00:05:51.260 --> 00:05:58.600
 So that's the kind of thing you have to think of as you're concatenating stuff together.

00:05:58.600 --> 00:06:03.540
 And the key thing is the request get guess, that came from the user.

00:06:03.540 --> 00:06:10.160
 And so we think the user's going to be nice, but a user with bad intent can send data that

00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:13.800
 they carefully construct to cause the maximum trouble.

00:06:13.800 --> 00:06:18.200
 But if you just escape your data before you concatenate it, there's nothing they can do

00:06:18.200 --> 00:06:20.620
 about it.

00:06:20.620 --> 00:06:28.320
 So another of the views is where we're going to parse the parameter off of the URL itself.

00:06:28.320 --> 00:06:33.080
 These URLs are a little prettier sometimes than the question mark keyword equals value.

00:06:33.080 --> 00:06:35.760
 And so let's take a look at this.

00:06:35.760 --> 00:06:42.520
 The way you do this is you, in your URL patterns, you have a path and instead of just having

00:06:42.520 --> 00:06:52.640
 the path name, the view function name, you actually have this bracket int colon guess

00:06:52.640 --> 00:06:53.640
 bracket.

00:06:53.640 --> 00:06:56.880
 And what that is, and you can go look this up in the Django documentation, there's a

00:06:56.880 --> 00:06:58.800
 whole series of these things.

00:06:58.800 --> 00:07:05.240
 That says the parameter after the word rest is an integer and please pass it in as the

00:07:05.240 --> 00:07:06.680
 parameter guess.

00:07:06.680 --> 00:07:10.120
 So I've chosen the name to pass it in as a parameter.

00:07:10.120 --> 00:07:15.900
 And then once Django sees this, it pulls that 41 off and hands it to us.

00:07:15.900 --> 00:07:18.280
 So we don't have to tear the URL apart.

00:07:18.280 --> 00:07:21.120
 Actually in this request object, we do get the URL.

00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:25.100
 We can do a bunch of splits and fool around, but nah, it doesn't matter.

00:07:25.100 --> 00:07:27.160
 Let's let Django do all that work.

00:07:27.160 --> 00:07:30.120
 Let's just tell it we want that parameter after the word rest.

00:07:30.120 --> 00:07:36.140
 It's supposed to be an integer and pass it to me in the variable guess.

00:07:36.140 --> 00:07:38.720
 And then that same 41 comes in.

00:07:38.720 --> 00:07:41.880
 I am clearly escaping it before I concatenate it.

00:07:41.880 --> 00:07:48.600
 And then I return a text-based HTML response with some HTML back to the browser.

00:07:48.600 --> 00:07:53.160
 So this escape is there just because of cross-site scripting.

00:07:53.160 --> 00:07:56.320
 I'm still taking this value, still coming from the user.

00:07:56.320 --> 00:08:01.160
 So if any value comes from the user, you have to properly escape it before you show it to

00:08:01.160 --> 00:08:02.160
 them.

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:08.800
 Now, those are all function-based, which are sort of a lower level.

00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:13.360
 We haven't got to the point where we're talking about forms, but eventually in those lower

00:08:13.360 --> 00:08:18.640
 level functions, you have to check whether you got a get request or a post request.

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:23.560
 Post request often comes from forms.

00:08:23.560 --> 00:08:31.160
 And so this class-based view allows us to give a method for get and a method for post

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:36.600
 and let Django pick whether it's a get or a post.

00:08:36.600 --> 00:08:40.160
 And this is an object-oriented, an object, and if you're a little rusty on objects, I've

00:08:40.160 --> 00:08:44.920
 got a URL there on pythonforeverybody.com to review just like what a self is.

00:08:44.920 --> 00:08:49.000
 I'm not going to cover all that.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:55.560
 In the path command, you just have a string that comes after the application, routing

00:08:55.560 --> 00:08:56.860
 to this.

00:08:56.860 --> 00:09:02.520
 The main view, as view is something you got to add to it because main view is a class,

00:09:02.520 --> 00:09:06.660
 not a function, but as view is a function.

00:09:06.660 --> 00:09:10.040
 And then we have to create a method get.

00:09:10.040 --> 00:09:16.400
 Self of course is just part of Python's object-oriented work request is that first parameter.

00:09:16.400 --> 00:09:21.760
 And so this one here is just the stock response, and I just like the other ones I returned

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:24.680
 on HTTP response.

00:09:24.680 --> 00:09:28.880
 It's like this looks a little more complex than the other one, did the same thing, but

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:33.720
 it turns out there is tons of things that we can do, and inheritance, the fact it's

00:09:33.720 --> 00:09:38.720
 a class, there are so many things about object-oriented programming that over the next few lectures

00:09:38.720 --> 00:09:43.840
 we're going to really take advantage of this, and we ultimately will rarely write the old

00:09:43.840 --> 00:09:48.620
 school function-based view, we'll do class-based views.

00:09:48.620 --> 00:09:53.400
 And so we can also pass parameters to class-based views just like we can pass them to function-based

00:09:53.400 --> 00:09:54.400
 views.

00:09:54.400 --> 00:10:01.520
 So you say, okay, with a prefix of remain, slug is a kind of string, and then guess is

00:10:01.520 --> 00:10:07.640
 the parameter, so that says pull the string after the word remain off, right, views is

00:10:07.640 --> 00:10:14.760
 the name of the view, remain is the view within the application, and then this third parameter

00:10:14.760 --> 00:10:20.240
 is the guess, and it's automatically parsed and handed to us in guess, and then we're

00:10:20.240 --> 00:10:25.200
 going to respond to a get request, self, of course, is the object-oriented thing, here's

00:10:25.200 --> 00:10:30.560
 the whole request, and guess is that little piece that comes off of the end of the URL,

00:10:30.560 --> 00:10:36.880
 we're going to create a response by escaping the user-provided guess bit so that if the

00:10:36.880 --> 00:10:42.200
 user puts something nasty in for cross-site scripting, ha-ha, we stop them from doing

00:10:42.200 --> 00:10:43.200
 that.

00:10:43.200 --> 00:10:52.440
 So that produces the same kind of output, your guess was abc12342xyzzy.

00:10:52.440 --> 00:10:58.480
 So talking about return values, everything we've shown you up till now is your basic

00:10:58.480 --> 00:11:03.320
 200 okay, which means you ask for a page, I gave you a page.

00:11:03.320 --> 00:11:08.120
 You're probably familiar with 404 not found, which means you ask for a page, that page

00:11:08.120 --> 00:11:10.020
 doesn't exist.

00:11:10.020 --> 00:11:15.400
 There is another kind of response that's not actually a page, which is a response header

00:11:15.400 --> 00:11:21.720
 that says, you know what, it's not like you made a mistake, but you're at the wrong place,

00:11:21.720 --> 00:11:26.920
 and it's called a redirect, and 302 means I know where you're supposed to be and it

00:11:26.920 --> 00:11:32.760
 isn't here, and it was originally used for sites that would move, and it's all handled

00:11:32.760 --> 00:11:39.800
 by the location header on the HTTP response, and so we send a redirect response, which

00:11:39.800 --> 00:11:46.520
 is a 302 with the location header being sent, and it uses a URL, and when the browser gets

00:11:46.520 --> 00:11:53.800
 that 302 and a location header, it doesn't show you what it just got, but it immediately

00:11:53.800 --> 00:12:00.600
 gets that URL, and then shows you that URL, and the original idea was that if you rename

00:12:00.600 --> 00:12:04.880
 a domain or something, you wanted to have the old domain, redirect web browsers and

00:12:04.880 --> 00:12:11.160
 search engines use these 302s, there's also a 301 header that can be used to redirect

00:12:11.160 --> 00:12:16.400
 all this stuff, but now we use it for all kinds of things, and it's very much a controller

00:12:16.400 --> 00:12:18.840
 function if you go to model view controller.

00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:22.900
 Controller says, okay, we're done with that, but I want your browser to go over there,

00:12:22.900 --> 00:12:29.300
 so that routing, that sort of routing the browser, changing the browser, putting the

00:12:29.300 --> 00:12:34.220
 browser where you want it to be, that's part of the application's controller phase.

00:12:34.220 --> 00:12:41.340
 So we can send a redirect from a Django view, and so here we go, if you go to this bounce,

00:12:41.340 --> 00:12:46.360
 it's going to actually not end up at this, it's gonna bounce it to somewhere else, and

00:12:46.360 --> 00:12:50.880
 in the path, we just say if you go to the bounce view, run to this function, this is

00:12:50.880 --> 00:12:56.040
 not a class-based function, this is an old-school function, and so the request data is passed

00:12:56.040 --> 00:13:02.760
 in, and instead of now returning an HTTP response, which we would put in here HTML, we are doing

00:13:02.760 --> 00:13:08.080
 an HTTP response, redirect, and now we put a URL, and what we're saying with this whole

00:13:08.080 --> 00:13:15.700
 thing is you're at the wrong place, please browser, when you get this response back,

00:13:15.700 --> 00:13:21.400
 go here, so it's like it bounces to the browser, and then bounces back, and then reads that

00:13:21.400 --> 00:13:28.120
 URL, so, and you don't, you can have some output, but folks generally don't need output

00:13:28.120 --> 00:13:30.200
 when you're doing a redirect.

00:13:30.200 --> 00:13:35.960
 So if you take a look at that bounce, watching it in your network console in a JavaScript

00:13:35.960 --> 00:13:40.800
 debugger, what you see is you see a set of three requests, actually just two, you'll

00:13:40.800 --> 00:13:47.800
 see the first request is going to bounce, and if we take a look at this request, we

00:13:47.800 --> 00:13:53.440
 see that it's a 302, it's kind of small, you see we got a 302, which tells the browser

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:59.680
 something's wrong, I'm not at the right place, and then also the server sends the location

00:13:59.680 --> 00:14:04.960
 header that says this is where you're supposed to be, and the browser immediately turns around

00:14:04.960 --> 00:14:13.640
 and does a get to that URL, simple.htm, and then that's what we see, and then this 404,

00:14:13.640 --> 00:14:20.280
 interestingly, the three statuses I talked to you about, is because at this new location,

00:14:20.280 --> 00:14:27.360
 djfree.com/simple.htm, there's no favicon, remember the favicon is the thing that shows

00:14:27.360 --> 00:14:33.480
 up like right there in the top tab bars, the favicon, and I don't have a favicon, at least

00:14:33.480 --> 00:14:38.360
 not now, or djfree, I should put a favicon there, but we get to see a 404, and all that

00:14:38.360 --> 00:14:42.440
 means is the browser looked for a favicon and didn't find it.

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:48.800
 So we see a 302, which is moved, with a location header, and then we see a get, which returns

00:14:48.800 --> 00:14:53.640
 then a 200, which is a success, and we see the document, and then we see a 404, because

00:14:53.640 --> 00:15:01.060
 it tries to grab the favicon, and so the HTML you get back from djfree.com/simple.htm, that's

00:15:01.060 --> 00:15:07.040
 this simple page with a simple link, okay, so that's how the redirect works.

